Report Cards
-----------------------------------------------------------

Welcome back to The Daily Courant, your afternoon digest of Puck=E2=80=99s =
best new reporting.

=C2=A0

Today, we lead with Dylan Byers=E2=80=99s insider chronicle of ESPN=E2=80=
=99s messy split with Major League Baseball, which was decidedly not mutual=
, despite commissioner Rob Manfred=E2=80=99s spin. For now, the blowup will=
 hurt baseball=E2=80=99s popularity, but could it also set the stage for a =
more consumer-friendly bundle?

=C2=A0

Plus, below the fold: Leigh Ann Caldwell reveals the Democrats=E2=80=99 tim=
ely embrace of Sanders-inflected anti-billionaire messaging. Bill Cohan gab=
s with the indefatigable Andrew Ross Sorkin about his new tome on the Great=
 Depression. Julie Davich offers a midseason auction update surrounding the=
 recent postwar and contemporary art sales. Marion
Maneker chronicles the highs and lows of Frieze L.A. And Sarah Shapiro illu=
minates how the new season of HBO=E2=80=99s The White Lotus ignited a wave =
of successful collaborations.

Meanwhile, on the pods: Big East commissioner Val Ackerman joins John Ouran=
d on The Varsity to break down how the basketball-centric conference thrive=
s in a football-dominated landscape. On Impolitic, John
Heilemann rings up former U.S. attorney Joyce Vance to discuss the perplexi=
ng Eric Adams case. And on The Powers That Be, Jon Kelly reunites with Pete=
r Hamby for a rollicking discussion about how the media is navigating Trump=
 II.

